data.content:
Here's what changes for each item in .NET 10:

---

### 1. `WebHostBuilder` → `WebApplicationBuilder`
`WebHost.CreateDefaultBuilder()` is **removed**. Migrate to the minimal hosting model:
```csharp
// Before (.NET 9)
var host = WebHost.CreateDefaultBuilder(args)
    .UseStartup<Startup>()
    .Build();

// After (.NET 10)
var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);
// Move Startup.ConfigureServices() contents here
var app = builder.Build();
// Move Startup.Configure() contents here
app.Run();
```

---

### 2. `.WithOpenApi()` removed
The `WithOpenApi()` endpoint extension is **removed**. Use OpenAPI document/operation transformers via `AddOpenApi()` options instead:
```csharp
// Before
app.MapGet("/items", () => ...).WithOpenApi();

// After — customize via transformers
builder.Services.AddOpenApi(options =>
{
    options.AddOperationTransformer((operation, context, ct) =>
    {
        // per-operation customization here
        return Task.CompletedTask;
    });
});
app.MapOpenApi();
```

---

### 3. `<IncludeOpenAPIAnalyzers>` removed
This MSBuild property **no longer has any effect**. Remove it from your `.csproj`. The analyzers it enabled are no longer shipped.

---

### 4. `Microsoft.Extensions.ApiDescription.Client` (NSwag codegen)
The build-time OpenAPI document generation is now built into the framework via `Microsoft.Extensions.ApiDescription.Server` (pulled in automatically by `Microsoft.AspNetCore.OpenApi`). For client code generation, replace the NSwag MSBuild-based pipeline with the **`dotnet openapi`** CLI tool or `Microsoft.Extensions.ApiDescription.Client` v10, which consumes the new built-in OpenAPI document format. Verify your NSwag version supports .NET 10's generated document schema.

---

### 5. `IActionContextAccessor` as singleton
Manual `services.AddSingleton<IActionContextAccessor, ActionContextAccessor>()` is **deprecated**. Use the new extension method which registers it with the correct lifetime:
```csharp
// Before
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IActionContextAccessor, ActionContextAccessor>();

// After
builder.Services.AddActionContextAccessor();
```

---

### 6. `IPNetwork` in `ForwardedHeadersOptions.KnownNetworks`
The custom `Microsoft.AspNetCore.HttpOverrides.IPNetwork` type is **removed**. Use the BCL `System.Net.IPNetwork` (introduced in .NET 8):
```csharp
// Before
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.HttpOverrides;
options.KnownNetworks.Add(new IPNetwork(IPAddress.Parse("10.0.0.0"), 8));

// After
options.KnownNetworks.Add(new System.Net.IPNetwork(IPAddress.Parse("10.0.0.0"), 8));
```
The constructor signature is the same (`IPAddress, int`), so only the `using`/type reference changes.

---

### 7. `AddRazorRuntimeCompilation()` removed
Razor runtime compilation is **removed** in .NET 10. The `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Razor.RuntimeCompilation` package is no longer available. Use **`dotnet watch`** (hot reload) for dev-time Razor editing instead:
```bash
dotnet watch run
```
Remove the package reference and any `AddRazorRuntimeCompilation()` calls.

---

### 8. 401 → login page redirect (cookie auth)
.NET 10 automatically suppresses cookie-auth redirects for endpoints that don't expect HTML responses (minimal APIs, `[ApiController]`). If you still need explicit control:
```csharp
builder.Services.ConfigureApplicationCookie(options =>
{
    options.Events.OnRedirectToLogin = context =>
    {
        context.Response.StatusCode = StatusCodes.Status401Unauthorized;
        return Task.CompletedTask;
    };
});
```
For most API projects migrating to the minimal hosting model, this now works correctly out of the box — API endpoints receive a `401` status code instead of a `302` redirect.

---

### Summary checklist
| Item | Action |
|---|---|
| `WebHostBuilder` | Rewrite to `WebApplication.CreateBuilder()` |
| `.WithOpenApi()` | Replace with `AddOpenApi()` + transformers |
| `IncludeOpenAPIAnalyzers` | Delete from csproj |
| NSwag codegen | Update packages; verify compatibility |
| `IActionContextAccessor` | Use `AddActionContextAccessor()` |
| `IPNetwork` | Switch to `System.Net.IPNetwork` |
| Razor runtime compilation | Remove; use `dotnet watch` |
| 401 redirects | Now correct by default for APIs |
